To perform the task without using loops or recursion, you can use C++ standard library functions including `std::iota`, `std::transform`, and `std::accumulate` to replace the loops:
```c
#include <iostream>
#include <numeric>
#include <vector>
#include <cmath>
#include <algorithm>

int powersum(int n, int k)
{
	std::vector<int> powers(n);
	std::iota(powers.begin(), powers.end(), 1);
	std::transform(powers.begin(), powers.end(), powers.begin(), [k](int i) {
	return int(std::pow(double(i), double(k)));
	});
	int sum = std::accumulate(powers.begin(), powers.end(), 0);
	return sum;
}
```

In this example, a vector of integers from 1 to n is created with `std::iota`. Then, the `std::pow` function is applied to every element with `std::transform`. Finally, the powers are summed up with `std::accumulate`.

To focus the first element of the form and to hide the form when the button is clicked again, you can modify the JavaScript code as follows:

JavaScript:
```
const btn = document.getElementById("showFormBtn");
const form = document.getElementById("form");

btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
  if (form.style.display === "block") {
    form.style.display = "none";
  } else {
    form.style.display = "block";
    form.elements[0].focus();
  }
});
```
In this code, the JavaScript checks the display property of the form. If the display property is "block", the form is hidden by setting the display property to "none". If the display property is not "block", the form is shown by setting the display property to "block" and focusing the first element of the form using the focus() method.

